The Vietnam War in American Film: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Undergraduate Film & Television Admissions About the Program Course Offerings Summer Courses Showcase Internships Facilities Special Projects First Run & Festivals Calendar of Events News TSOA FTV Wiki Admin & Faculty Alumni Blog Facebook Twitter YouTube  home > Undergraduate Film & TV        The Vietnam War in American Film  H72.0326  4 Credits Instructor(s): Stefano Ciaamaroni Tuesday 6:00 - 10:00PM    This course will explore the representation of the Vietnam War in American fiction and documentary film, seeking to assess the role that cinema has played in both repressing and uncovering the ideological conflicts and social contradictions that surrounded this national tragedy. Our journey begins in the mid-1950s, with Hollywood’s sympathetic portrayal of France’s colonial struggle in Indochina/Vietnam ( The Quiet American , China Gate ), moves across the 1960s to consider a number of political documentaries that either legitimized ( Why Vietnam and Know Your Enemy ) or radically contested ( In the Year of the Pig ) the U.S. military involvement in the region. The course then tackles the American fiction film’s initial inability to engage the war if not through allegory ( Night of the Living Dead ) or subtextually ( Taxi Driver ). We will subsequently segue into the ideologically contentious 1980s, when revisionist fantasies ( Rambo , Uncommon Valor , Missing in Action ) collided with the “realistic” ambitions of a new wave of combat films ( Platoon , Hamburger Hill , Full Metal Jacket ). Finally, we will conclude the class with a point-of-view reversal, pitting an American production’s attempt to offer a Vietnamese perspective on the conflict ( Heaven and Earth ) against a Vietnamese combat film ( The Abandoned Field-Free Fire Zone ). The Vietnam War in American Film: Tisch School of the Arts at NYU                           Skip to content        Undergraduate Film & Television Admissions About the Program Course Offerings Summer Courses Showcase Internships Facilities Special Projects First Run & Festivals Calendar of Events News TSOA FTV Wiki Admin & Faculty Alumni Blog Facebook Twitter YouTube  home > Undergraduate Film & TV        The Vietnam War in American Film  H72.0326  4 Credits Instructor(s): Stefano Ciaamaroni Tuesday 6:00 - 10:00PM    This course will explore the representation of the Vietnam War in American fiction and documentary film, seeking to assess the role that cinema has played in both repressing and uncovering the ideological conflicts and social contradictions that surrounded this national tragedy. Our journey begins in the mid-1950s, with Hollywood’s sympathetic portrayal of France’s colonial struggle in Indochina/Vietnam ( The Quiet American , China Gate ), moves across the 1960s to consider a number of political documentaries that either legitimized ( Why Vietnam and Know Your Enemy ) or radically contested ( In the Year of the Pig ) the U.S. military involvement in the region. The course then tackles the American fiction film’s initial inability to engage the war if not through allegory ( Night of the Living Dead ) or subtextually ( Taxi Driver ). We will subsequently segue into the ideologically contentious 1980s, when revisionist fantasies ( Rambo , Uncommon Valor , Missing in Action ) collided with the “realistic” ambitions of a new wave of combat films ( Platoon , Hamburger Hill , Full Metal Jacket ). Finally, we will conclude the class with a point-of-view reversal, pitting an American production’s attempt to offer a Vietnamese perspective on the conflict ( Heaven and Earth ) against a Vietnamese combat film ( The Abandoned Field-Free Fire Zone ).
